The electroluminescence from the device was visible to naked eyes, white light with a bluish color (Figure 6
                     ). The corresponding electroluminescence spectrum was found to be broad, covering a wide range of the visible spectral region. Shown in Figure 7
                      is a comparison of the electroluminescence spectrum with the photoluminescence spectra (obtained with multiple excitation wavelengths) of the corresponding carbon dots. Apparently the electronic excitation could generate the emissive excited states that would require photoexcitations at multiple wavelengths. While the comparison is rather rough without any quantitative value, the general overlap between the electroluminescence spectrum and the collection of multiple photoluminescence spectra seems to suggest that the recombination zone is within the carbon dots layer, with the PVK layer serving primarily the function of hole-transport. The electroluminescence spectra were not sensitive to variations in the applied voltage (11–15V), as also shown in Figure 6. From the electroluminescence spectrum, the chromaticity CIE coordinate (0.25, 0.24) for 15V applied biases was calculated (Figure 6).
